<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-05-26T08:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-05-26T08:00:00-05:00" n="371" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d371">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">800.51W89 Belgium/190: Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Belgium (<persName corresp="#p_MF2" type="from">Mayer</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Brussels</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-05-26T14:00:00+01:00">May
                                        26, 1932—2 p.m.</date>
                                    <lb/> [Received May 26—9:50 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>43. My 42, May 24, 6 p.m. Foreign Office has just informed me that
                                they have telephoned Ambassador May instructions to the effect that
                                full powers are going forward to him by mail to sign the President’s
                                1-year debt postponement agreement.</p>
                            <p>The Foreign Office added that they are suggesting through Mr.
                                    <persName corresp="#p_MP1">May</persName> a slight rectification
                                of detail as to the amount to be paid under this agreement the
                                latter being a small saving to the Belgian Government by semi-annual
                                rather than annual payments. The Foreign Office believes that the
                                British Government are making the same suggestion to us.</p>
                            <p>Repeated to Paris.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_MF2">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Mayer</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>